  "texts": [
    "If the idea of an order present wherever actions are done with intention were meant to be used to describe \"actual mental processes\" that occur prior to each and every intentional action, she comments, \"it would in general be quite absurd\" (p. 80).Anscombe's point here can be put by saying that the causes of intentional actions are much more various than the standard story, with its constraint that what causes an intentional action must also rationalise it, can allow.",
    "Recall Davidson's 'trivial' action Synthese (2025) 205:47 description: \"I move my body in the way required to tie my shoelaces.\"",
    "His account entails that a state with something like this content, at least, must be causally poised to bring about any such action.",
    "This is what Anscombe denies, claiming a) that not all occurrent mental causes of action rationalise, and b) that much of what is typically called on to rationalise an action, being either a long past event or a prospective state of affairs, is not poised to cause it.",
    "Answers to the question 'Why?'"
  ],
